Exercise

In each of these figures, what are the features at \(A\) and \(B\)?

  1. \(A\) is a: [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]

    \(B\) is a: [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]

  2. \(A\) is a: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]

    \(B\) is a: [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]

generalfeedback.text:
1. From feature \(A\), depending on the direction we move in we can either gain or loose height. Hence, \(A\) is a saddle point.

    From feature \(B\), no matter what direction we move in we always gain height. Hence, \(B\) is a local minimum.

  2. From feature \(A\), no matter what direction we move in we always loose height. Hence, \(A\) is a local maximum.

    From feature \(B\), depending on the direction we move in we can either gain or loose height. Hence, \(B\) is a saddle point.
